Doubling Down on Our Minds
If there=E2=80=99s one key message I want you to take away from reading thi=
s, it=E2=80=99s that new knowledge transfer technologies unlock new and bet=
ter ways of thinking.=C2=A0
Human brains are not static; they=E2=80=99re dynamic, and capable of improv=
ing. New technologies can spur those improvements. The phonetic alphabet an=
d the printing press didn=E2=80=99t just help spread ideas, they made us sm=
arter in the process. While we=E2=80=99re still early in the development of=
 AI, chess and Go provide early proof points that we=E2=80=99re not done im=
proving.=C2=A0
Genetic evolution is a slow process, but our minds haven=E2=80=99t evolved =
through genetics alone for millennia. As Daniel Dennett highlights in From =
Bacteria to Bach and Back [ https://substack.com/redirect/97fa1148-4c30-433=
2-8a17-1487ba77bd7f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8=
-6m8ExkRNpU ], our brains have coevolved with memes, =E2=80=9Cwords strivin=
g to reproduce.=E2=80=9D New information =E2=80=93 new words, ideas, argume=
nts, images =E2=80=93 can be =E2=80=9Cdownloaded to your necktop,=E2=80=9D =
where it mixes and mashes with all of the other memes you=E2=80=99ve downlo=
aded and becomes part of your personal reasoning capabilities.=C2=A0
Phonetic language, the printing press, and AI serve to distribute memes fur=
ther and faster, so that we can upgrade our minds and provide fresh new ins=
ights.=C2=A0
Dennett addresses AI directly in the closing paragraphs of his 2017 book, w=
riting:=C2=A0
Or we may continue to thrive, in an environment we have created with the he=
lp of artifacts that do most of the heavy cognitive lifting their own way, =
in an age of post-intelligent design. There is not just coevolution between=
 memes and genes; there is codependence between our minds=E2=80=99 top-down=
 reasoning abilities and the bottom-up uncomprehending talents of our anima=
l brains. And if our future follows the trajectory of our past =E2=80=94 so=
mething that is partly in our control =E2=80=93 our artificial intelligence=
s will continue to be dependent on us even as we become more warily depende=
nt on them.
This separation of powers and codependence is what I=E2=80=99m talking abou=
t. It mirrors the phonetic alphabet and the printing press. Give them more =
of the heavy cognitive lifting so that we might focus on our minds=E2=80=99=
 top-down reasoning abilities, on the rare and novel sparks of insight that=
 people like Anaximander were able to conjure.=C2=A0
I don=E2=80=99t know what those insights will be. What I do know, what I ha=
ve a strong human intuition about, at least, is that if we are at the foot =
of one of these technological/human insight-powered turning points, people =
are going to spend a lot of time and effort training their minds in order t=
o generate those insights.=C2=A0
Far from giving up on learning because AI is smarter than us, pushing our b=
rains is only going to get more popular, and we=E2=80=99re only going to ge=
t better, just like we did in chess and Go.=C2=A0
By pushing what AI can do and learning how it thinks, we=E2=80=99ll learn m=
ore about how our own minds work, and what makes them unique.=C2=A0
We=E2=80=99ll come up with wild theories, like this one from Kevin Kelly [ =
https://substack.com/redirect/7a3ef58a-caa7-4b57-9ba2-51d9098a218d?j=3DeyJ1=
IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] =E2=80=93 =E2=
=80=9CThat our brains tend to produce dreams at all times, and that during =
waking hours, our brains tame the dream machine into perception and truthin=
ess.=E2=80=9D He came up with it while playing with generative AI, by notic=
ing similarities between AI=E2=80=99s hallucinations and our dreams and mak=
ing a uniquely human leap based on his intuition.=C2=A0
Wild theories based on facts, experience, and intuition (which we=E2=80=99l=
l then subject to the scientific method, of course) will be at a premium. I=
 suspect that we=E2=80=99re going to see an explosion in the popularity of =
things like meditation, breathwork, psychedelics, lucid dreaming, ongoing e=
ducation, sleep, nootropics, writing, walks in nature, tutoring, exercise, =
alcohol-cutting, in-person group experiences, debates, and all sorts of way=
s that might assist in their creation.
We can even use AI to help us train in new, personalized ways, like Greg Mu=
shen used ChatGPT to get himself addicted to running:=C2=A0
This tweet is a good metaphor, because while AI can assist in our training,=
 we still have to go out and run the miles ourselves. Part of what makes hu=
man insight valuable and different is the hands-on experience of doing, of =
feeling the frustration when something doesn=E2=80=99t quite make sense, of=
 feeling the joy of figuring something out after a long struggle.=C2=A0
We=E2=80=99ve all worked for middle managers too far removed from the day-t=
o-day to add much value; we=E2=80=99re at risk of something similar happeni=
ng if we hand too much of our thinking over to AI. Intuition is earned.
Some people will be happy letting AI do the grunt work. Not everyone will s=
ee AI=E2=80=99s advance as a challenge to meet, just as I have not taken ad=
vantage of chess and Go engines to become better at either of those games. =
But I think, as in chess and Go, more people will get smarter. The process =
will produce more geniuses, broadly defined, ready to deliver the fresh, hu=
man insights required to ignite the next intellectual revolution.=C2=A0
If we can walk the line, the result, I think, will be a deeper understandin=
g of the universe and ourselves, and a meaningful next leg in the neverendi=
ng quest to understand and shape our realities.
